The P-EBT program reopened today for those families that did not apply when it was previously open.

This is for students in Catahoula Parish schools during the last school year under the age of 18. It is a one-time benefit of $285

Please remember that this is only if the child was not claimed on an application prior to June 15th. Any child previously claimed will not be accepted on a new application.

For more information and to apply, please visit:
http://www.dcfs.louisiana.gov/page/pebt-program#faq

post_text:
All Catahoula Parish Schools will be closed Tuesday, September 1st. The status of Wednesday will be determined at a later time.

The Central Office will reopen on Tuesday at 10 AM and the regularly scheduled School Board Meeting will be held at 6 PM.

The district currently has two schools with no power, no internet service to the district, and will need to get food deliveries once power has been restored to all schools. The administration will determine closures on a day-by-day basis until things return to normal.

post_text: We are proud to introduce the new principal of Block High School, Ms. Marilyn Alexander-Turner. Ms. Turner is a retiree from Mississippi with experience as an administrator, coordinator, principal, and supervisor. When she retired, she was the Director of Federal Programs. Most recently, Ms. Turner has been teaching in the Catahoula Parish School system with time spent at both Block High School and Jonesville Elementary in special education. Since her appointment, Ms. Turner has hit the ground running and is looking forward to a great year ahead for BHS!

OFFICIAL NOTICE:
All Catahoula Parish Schools will start on Friday, August 21st

This is a one-week delay.

Students in Option 1 do not have to notify anyone, they report to school on the 21st.

Parents choosing Option 2 K12 must contact the school system at COVID19@catahoulaschools.com by August 17th if you have not contacted us. That will be the deadline for K12. (Mr. Chauvin will register you student with K12 so please do not try to register the student yourself.)

Parents of virtual students will be contacted soon with dates and times that they can pick up their children‚Äôs devices. They will be picked up from the schools and teachers will show them how to use the google classroom.

Hand sanitizer dispensers will be installed in each classroom next week.

Water dispensers with cups will be delivered either this week or early next week to all schools.

Professional carpet cleaning of all schools with carpet will be completed this week.

post_text:
Graduation week starts tonight! While these ceremonies won‚Äôt be exactly like those in the past, we are happy to be able to offer an in person graduation for all of our schools. Please remember the following guidelines:

1. These are all ticketed events only.
2. Families will be seated together and will be socially distanced from other families.
3. Masks are required except for those aged 2 or under and persons with severe breathing issues.
4. We ask all attendees to not gather within the facilities or the parking lots with other families.
5. At the end of the ceremony at each school, each graduate will leave with their family from the building at the same time. We ask everyone to move directly to their vehicles at that time.

These are trying times and we know these guidelines are hard on families and the graduates, however, it is the only way we can safely hold in person ceremonies.

Congratulations to the Class of 2020! You are #CatahoulaStrong!!

post_text: Remember, the free virtual summer school is available to all Catahoula students, including high school students who did not earn all of their credits this year.
text: Remember, the free virtual summer school is available to all Catahoula students, including high school students who did not earn all of their credits this year.

post_text:
Catahoula Parish will be offering a free virtual summer school to any student who was not promoted to the next grade and to any high school student who did not receive credit in a course. This is for all grades K to 11. To be signed up for this program please email the following information to COVID19@catahoulaschools.com:
Student name, grade, subject needed
Parent name, email address, phone #
Students will begin to be placed in the online classes Monday of next week (June 8th) and you will be contacted by Mr. Chauvin from the central office with class information.

If you have already signed up for summer school, please print the invoice where you paid and submit it to Mr. Chauvin and you will be reimbursed what you paid.

You may contact Mr. Chauvin at 318-744-5727 ext 120 for more information.

post_text:
Catahoula Parish School Board is proud to be able to offer free eBook access to students to enjoy this summer through First Book. These books can be read on iPhones or Android devices. We have 500 codes available for 10 free ebooks (first come first served) per student. If you are interested, please email the student's name to COVID19@catahoulaschools.com and we will send you the code, PIN #, and the instructions to download the app and books. ALL students in Catahoula Parish schools under the age of 18 are eligible for the new Pandemic-EBT benefits of $285 per student. Unused benefits roll over month-to-month but must be used within 365 days.

The portal opens for applications on Monday, May 18, 2020, and closes on June 8, 2020, so don't delay applying.

The portal and FAQs are located at http://www.dcfs.louisiana.gov/page/pebt-program#faq

Again, every student in Catahoula Parish Schools under 18 are eligible for this. Please don't miss this one-time opportunity!

post_text: At today's board meeting, the board adopted a 4-day per week school calendar for the 2020-2021 school year. The calendar has been uploaded to the parish website at cpsbla.org. School will begin for students on Friday, August 14th. Students will attend Tuesday through Friday of each week with 2 exceptions: the week of Veteran's Day (students attend Mon., Tues., Thur. Fri.) and 2 weeks in April during testing where the students will attend 5 days per week. This 4-day schedule has worked well in other districts and administrators have taken pointers from those districts on how to implement the calendar successfully.

post_text:
Q: What resources are available if students do not have internet at home and/or need assistance with
accessing the Internet?
A: FCC Chairman Ajit Pai has launched the ‚ÄúKeep Americans Connected Pledge,‚Äù which many broadband
carriers have signed. For the next 60 days, its provisions will:
‚óè not terminate service to any residential or small business customers because of their inability to
pay their bills due to the disruptions caused by the coronavirus pandemic;
‚óè waive any late fees that any residential or small business customers incur because of their
economic circumstances related to the coronavirus pandemic; and
‚óè open its Wi-Fi hotspots to any American who needs them.
Additionally, limited income households can apply for $5 to $10 per month internet access ( AT&T
Access , Cox Connect2Compete , CenturyLink Lifeline ). Charter Communication will offer free Spectrum
broadband and Wi-Fi access for 60 days to households with K-12 and/or college students who do not
already have a subscription.

Catahoula Parish School District has partnered with Baylor University and the USDA to provide meals to any student registered at one of our schools through the Emergency Meals to You Program. OFFICIAL STATEMENT 3/23/2020 REGARDING MEALS

Beginning at the completion of meal service today, 3/23/2020, Catahoula Parish Schools will suspend the pick-up meal service at all 4 locations. While we understand that the meal program is a very important service, we must consider the safety of our employees at this time. With the shortage of personal protective equipment, we cannot protect our employees as they prepare, pack, and distribute meals. We are exploring other options for our students and will continue to monitor the situation.

post_text: From one of our own teachers for 5th and 6th grade students. Have your children research.
shared_text:
Nesa Jordan-Barber is with Martha Walston and Matt-Amanda Brazell.
March 19 at 10:17 PM ¬∑

Well, I guess that my brain is always in teacher mode. If you have a 5th/6th grader, use current events to review social studies. (5th Grade)Ask:
1. Is Coronavirus zoonotic? Explain.
2. What does the Columbian Exchange explain? How does it help you somewhat grasp the concept of the Coronavirus?
Science: (6th Grade) Ask:
1. What are the 3 tenets of cell theory? Explain.
2. A virus is a parasite & a cell is the host. Explain this relationship.
3. What is a mutual obligate relationship? Explain an example.
********Fifth graders may be curious & want to research the sixth grade science.

post_text: Our National Park Service has various tools your children can use while at home. There are not only learning tools but live webcams where they can watch wild animals.
shared_text:
National Park Service
March 18 at 3:48 PM ¬∑

Every time I stay home, I‚Äôd rather be out, but every time I go out, I‚Äôd rather be home.

We hear ya. But even from home, you can discover amazing things about your parks. Did you know you can see what‚Äôs happening live at parks without leaving your home? Webcams allow you to get up close to wildlife without disturbing them. Learn more at https://www.nps.gov/subjects/watchingwildlife/webcams.htm

With topics ranging from A to Z, research a variety of park subjects and stories at https://www.nps.gov/learnandexplore/subjects.htm

Learn about the natural resources in parks, from the rocks under our feet to the sky overhead and everything in between at https://www.nps.gov/nature

Image: A brown bear staring intently while resting on a log at Katmai National Park & Preserve, Alaska. NPS/ J. Ehrlenbach

#FindYourPark #Staycation

post_text:
Where did #CatahoulaStrong come from?

Earlier this year, Jonesville Elementary Principal, Necie Barker, came up with the saying that our schools are Catahoula Strong. From that point on, in principal meetings and other times the saying was used repeatedly. When we were hit with the trying times we are currently facing, we felt that there was no better time than now to implement #CatahoulaStrong as our school district's public motto.

So, thanks Mrs. Barker! We appreciate you giving us a great motto to get us through this situation!

post_text:
OFFICIAL STATEMENT:

Update #1: All spring baseball and softball games are suspended from March 16th until April 13th. Practices will still be allowed at this time.

All Catahoula Parish Schools will be closed for students until April 13, 2020, from an Executive Order from Governor Edwards. All employees should report to work as normal Monday, March 16th. At that time we will work together to come up with methods to provide instructional materials to our students. If an employee is sick or experiencing any symptoms of illness, or if an employee has recently traveled to a city impacted by COVID 19, please contact your principal and do not report on Monday.

At this time, we do not have many details on how this will impact our year, but we will update regularly as we have new information. We apologize for the lack of information at this time, however, this is a fluid situation that will change over time.

Again: All students will not report to school until April 13th.
All employees will report to work Monday, March 16th, unless ill.

At that time we will work together to come up with methods to provide instructional materials to our students. If an employee is sick or experiencing any symptoms of illness, or if an employee has recently traveled to a city impacted by COVID 19, please contact your principal and do not report on Monday.

At this time, we do not have many details on how this will impact our year, but we will update regularly as we have new information. We apologize for the lack of information at this time, however, this is a fluid situation that will change over time.

post_text:
Yesterday, Catahoula Parish School System lost one of our own with the sudden passing of Ms. Judy Franklin. Judy went to work for the district in September of 1984 as a Secretary to the Supervisors at the School Board Annex in Jonesville. She worked her way up and became the Secretary to the Superintendent and was still in that position at her passing. Judy was a loyal and faithful employee who was loved by everyone that worked with her. As one of the longest-term Central Office employees, she had worked with many different people over the years and befriended all of them. Judy was not just a co-worker to us at the office, she was family. She will be greatly missed.

Arrangements are as follows:
Visitation, Thursday, Jan. 16th from 5 PM to 8 PM
Funeral, Friday, Jan. 17th at 2 PM
All services will be held at Young's Funeral Home in Jonesville

All Catahoula Parish Schools were already scheduled to be closed Friday due to Parent/Teacher Conference the night before.
The Central Office will now be closed in honor of Judy Franklin.
